🔥 The Code
const token = jwt.sign(
    { id: user._id },
    "secretkey",
    { expiresIn: "1h" }
);
🧠 One-Line Meaning
👉 Create a secure identity token for the user after login
🔥 Break It Down (VERY CLEAR)
🟢 1. jwt.sign(...)

👉 Function used to create a token
sign = generate token
🟢 2. Payload
{ id: user._id }

👉 Data you want to store inside token
Example:
{
  "id": "65abc123..."
}

👉 This tells:
"Which user is logged in"
🟢 3. Secret Key
"secretkey"

👉 Used to secure/sign the token
Only server knows this
👉 Prevents tampering

🟢 4. Options
{ expiresIn: "1h" }
👉 Token will expire after 1 hour
🔥 What Token Looks Like
eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9...

👉 Looks random, but contains:

Header.Payload.Signature
🧠 What Happens When You Create Token?
🟢 Step 1: User Logs In
Email + Password → Verified
🟢 Step 2: Server Creates Token
jwt.sign(...)
🟢 Step 3: Server Sends Token
{
  "token": "abc123..."
}
🟢 Step 4: Client Stores Token
👉 In:
Postman
Browser (localStorage / cookies)
🔥 WHY DO WE CREATE TOKEN? (VERY IMPORTANT)
❓ Problem Without Token
👉 Server cannot remember user

Request 1 → login
Request 2 → who are you? ❌
✅ Solution: Token

👉 Token acts like:
ID Card 🎫

🔥 How Token Is Used
🟢 Client Sends Token
Authorization: Bearer TOKEN
🟢 Middleware Verifies
jwt.verify(token, "secretkey");

👉 Checks:
Is token valid?
Is it expired?
Is it tampered?
🟢 If Valid
Access granted ✅
🟢 If Invalid
Access denied ❌
🔥 Why Not Just Send User ID?

👉 Because:
User can modify it ❌

👉 Token is:
Signed + Secure ✅

//////////////////////
🧠 Internal Working (Simple)
When you create token:
jwt.sign(payload, secret)

👉 It:

Encodes payload
Adds signature using secret
Creates token
When you verify:
jwt.verify(token, secret)

👉 It:

Checks signature
Extracts payload
🔥 Final Flow (SUPER IMPORTANT)
Login:
User → verified → token created

Next Requests:
Client → sends token
Server → verifies token
→ allows access

